DHCP Server Configuration in Linux Step By Step Procedure:
---------------
1. Login as root user and configure yum repository. If you don't know how to configure it then click below link to watch the videos:
Yum configuration in RHEL 7:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-N09W...​

Yum configuration in RHEL 8:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cXqL5...​

2. Set the Static IP Address in your server.
#nmtui​
OR
# vim /etc/sysconfig/network-script/ifcfg-ens33

3. Install DHCP Packages from local yum repo.
# yum install -y dhcp*
port 67

4. Make proper changes in configuration (dhcpd.conf) file as per your requirements. You can also set static IP Addresses with it.
 # vim /etc/dhcp/dhcpd.conf
 if we open the above file we see file path mentioned below copy from /usr/share/doc/dhcp-server/dhcpd.conf.example to the above file 
 
 #
# DHCP Server Configuration file.
#   see /usr/share/doc/dhcp-server/dhcpd.conf.example
#   see dhcpd.conf(5) man page
#

# A slightly different configuration for an internal subnet.
subnet 10.5.5.0 netmask 255.255.255.224 {============================give subnet and netmask,  it should be 0 in the subnet 
  range 10.5.5.26 10.5.5.30;=========================================give ip range from start to end here from 26 to 30 they gave
  option domain-name-servers ns1.internal.example.org;-==============if we use domanin we can use it or else comment it
  option domain-name "internal.example.org";===================if we use domanin we can use it or else comment it
  option routers 10.5.5.1;=====================================if we use router we can use it or else comment it
  option broadcast-address 10.5.5.31;=============if  we can use it or else comment it
  default-lease-time 600;
  max-lease-time 7200;for every 7200 min it will chnage the ip as dhcp it is 


in dhcp we can set permanent ip for example printer, untill we change the ip it wont change and ip should be in dhcp range

# Fixed IP addresses can also be specified for hosts.   These addresses
# should not also be listed as being available for dynamic assignment.
# Hosts for which fixed IP addresses have been specified can boot using
# BOOTP or DHCP.   Hosts for which no fixed address is specified can only
# be booted with DHCP, unless there is an address range on the subnet
# to which a BOOTP client is connected which has the dynamic-bootp flag
# set.
host fantasia {========================give host name of the server 
  hardware ethernet 08:00:07:26:c0:a5;===========give hardware or  mac address in ifconfig  ether 00:0c:29:b1:6d:83 we can get 
  fixed-address fantasia.example.com;==============here we give ip  like this we give  fixed-address 192.168.120.160;



5. Start and enable DHCP service.
# systemctl start dhcpd
# systemctl enable dhcpd

Check the status of service if required.
# systemctl status dhcpd

6. Now test the configuration, login to client machine and restart the network manager.
# systemctl restart NetworkManager

7.Check the IP Address, which should be in range of configuration settings you have made in dhcpd.conf file.

You are done.

